              <h2>How the lumpsum calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This lumpsum calculator helps you estimate how a one-time
                investment can grow over time using compound interest. It also
                lets you work backwards from a goal amount or required return,
                and optionally adjust for inflation and taxes.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Future value of a lumpsum</h3>
              <p>
                When you invest a single amount <em>P</em> at an annual return
                <em>r</em> for <em>n</em> years, the future value (FV) is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Formula:</strong></p>
                <p>\( FV = P \times (1 + r)^{n} \)</p>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>P</strong> = initial lumpsum investment</li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>r</strong> = annual return (in decimal, e.g. 12% =
                    0.12)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>n</strong> = time in years (including fractional
                    years)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Required lumpsum for a target goal</h3>
              <p>
                If you know the target amount you want to reach, you can
                rearrange the formula to solve for the required lumpsum:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Formula:</strong></p>
                <p>\( P = \dfrac{FV}{(1 + r)^{n}} \)</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <strong>FV</strong> = target amount at the end of the period
                  </li>
                  <li><strong>P</strong> = one-time investment needed today</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Implied return (CAGR)</h3>
              <p>
                If you know how much you invested and what it grew to, the
                calculator can estimate the implied annual return (compound
                annual growth rate, or CAGR):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Formula:</strong></p>
                <p>\( r = \left(\dfrac{FV}{P}\right)^{1/n} - 1 \)</p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Inflation-adjusted (real) value</h3>
              <p>
                To understand the <em>purchasing power</em> of your future
                amount, the calculator can adjust for inflation. If inflation is
                <em>i</em> per year, the real value is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( FV_{\text{real}} = \dfrac{FV}{(1 + i)^{n}} \)</p>
              </div>

              <h3>5. After-tax value</h3>
              <p>
                If you pay a flat tax rate <em>t</em> on your gains, the
                post-tax amount is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( \text{Gains} = FV - P \)</p>
                <p>\( \text{Tax} = \text{Gains} \times t \)</p>
                <p>\( FV_{\text{after tax}} = FV - \text{Tax} \)</p>
              </div>

              <h2>When to use a lumpsum investment</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  You have a large bonus, inheritance, or savings to invest at
                  once.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You want to compare a one-time investment with a SIP
                  (Systematic Investment Plan).
                </li>
                <li>
                  You are planning for a specific goal like education, a house
                  down payment, or retirement.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Pros of lumpsum investing</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>More time in the market if invested early.</li>
                <li>Simple to manage – only one transaction.</li>
                <li>
                  Potentially higher returns if markets rise after you invest.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Risks and limitations</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Higher short-term risk if markets fall soon after you invest.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Assumes a constant average return, which is not guaranteed.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not automatically account for fund expenses or
                  transaction costs.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Is this calculator only for mutual funds?</h3>
              <p>
                No. You can use it for mutual funds, index funds, ETFs, stocks,
                bonds, or any investment that compounds at an expected annual
                rate. Just adjust the expected return to match the asset type
                and your risk profile.
              </p>

              <h3>What return should I assume?</h3>
              <p>
                There is no single correct number. Many investors use long-term
                historical averages:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Equity mutual funds / stocks: often 10–15% in nominal terms
                  (before inflation).
                </li>
                <li>Balanced funds: typically 7–11%.</li>
                <li>Debt funds / bonds: often 4–8%.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use conservative assumptions for planning and review your plan
                regularly.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I lose money with a lumpsum investment?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Market-linked investments can go down as well as up. The
                calculator shows mathematical projections based on your inputs,
